had a very good social life, and enjoyed great learning experiences. &#10;Both are now in full time employment, can mix with all ages, have no social problems and have had a great childhood. &#10;I just don't understand why people think the only place children can learn is school, life is about learning, you never stop learning, children learn all the time anywhere, we have so many resources now, times are changing. &#10;One of the biggest difference I see in home-educated children is how they can mix with all ages. In school you are all placed in aged related groups and you stay there, scared to stray from them in case you are laughed at for playing with someone younger than you. Where else in society does that happen, as soon as you get in the workplace you are mixing with all sort, its so alien. &#10;Dawn www.homeeducators.co.uk"/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1130" language="en" documentId="1186" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="blackburnyoung" date="31 July 2010 1:38am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6915989" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="1186" notes="" title="Home education: precious, not dangerous"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="74"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="75" end="372"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="373" end="490"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="491" end="715"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="716" end="1101"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="1102" end="1130"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 59"/></xmi:XMI>